hese questions through texts in philosophy, literature, and social science. Imperial Genus focuses on how notions of human generality mediated uncertainty between the transcendental and the empirical, the universal and the particular, and empire and colony. It shows how cosmopolitan cultural principles, the proletarian arts, and Pan-Asian imperial nationalism converged with practices of colonial governmentality. It is a genealogy of the various articulations of the human's genus-being within modern humanist thinking in East Asia, as well as an exploration of the limits of the human as both concept and historical figure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEssentialism (Philosophy) 0aEssentialism (Philosophy). 0aJapanese literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aKorean literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520964198?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520964198zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520964198/original  a978-3-11-062111-2 University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-064982-6 Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA